                { q: "The hole in the ozone layer over the Antarctic is smaller this year than last year, and the layer is now ( ) to recovery.", opts: ["of importance", "in question", "on track", "by contrast"], a: 2, explain: "To be 'on track to recovery' is an idiom meaning to make progress toward returning to a healthy or normal state." },
                { q: "By analyzing images of its surface taken by the rover, the NASA Curiosity has found evidence ( ) a stream once flowed on Mars.", opts: ["which", "where", "that", "what"], a: 2, explain: "The noun complement clause uses 'that' to describe the details of the evidence ('evidence that a stream once flowed')." },
                { q: "Some Americans spend hours in their cars every day, trapped in traffic jams, and burn fuel, ( ) they sit and wait.", opts: ["even as", "until when", "to the point", "on the way"], a: 0, explain: "The conjunction 'even as' means at the very same time that ('burn fuel even as they sit and wait')." },
                { q: "Venice is renowned for its canals, but now a majority of the city is under water as heavy rains and unusually high tides ( ) about 70 percent of the city.", opts: ["will flood", "is flooding", "was flooded", "have flooded"], a: 3, explain: "The present perfect tense 'have flooded' is correct because the action occurred recently and continues to affect Venice." },
                { q: "The organization says more than half of depression sufferers are not receiving treatment because many ( ) acknowledge their illness.", opts: ["cope with", "fail to", "hope to", "put up with"], a: 1, explain: "The phrase 'fail to' means to not do something, indicating sufferers do not acknowledge their illness." }
