            type: "mc",
            passage: "The journey of human communication from spoken words to structured written symbols represents one of the most profound transformations in history. Long before the invention of formal scripts, early humans relied on pictograms—simple drawings that physically represented concrete objects. While effective for simple, immediate labels, pictograms were fundamentally limited. They could not easily express abstract concepts, verbs, or complex grammatical relationships. A drawing of a leg could represent the limb itself, but conveying the action of 'running' or the abstract concept of 'speed' required a leap in symbolic complexity.<br><br>This leap occurred in ancient Mesopotamia with the development of cuneiform. Emerging around 3200 BCE, cuneiform began as pictographs but gradually evolved into stylized, wedge-shaped marks pressed into damp clay tablets with a reed stylus. Over centuries, these marks became increasingly abstract, representing syllables and sounds rather than physical objects. This transition from logographic writing (where a symbol represents a word or idea) to phonographic writing (where a symbol represents a sound) allowed for the recording of spoken language in all its complexity, enabling the creation of literature, legal codes, and historical chronicles.<br><br>While cuneiform flourished, other logographic systems developed, most notably Egyptian hieroglyphs and early Chinese oracle bone script. These systems were complex, requiring scribes to memorize thousands of unique characters. The administrative and economic demands of expanding trade routes, however, necessitated a simpler, more accessible system. This need was met by the Phoenicians, a seafaring civilization of the Mediterranean. Around 1050 BCE, they developed the Phoenician alphabet—a phonetic system consisting of just 22 characters, each representing a single consonant sound.<br><br>By discarding logographic symbols and focusing purely on the sounds of speech, the Phoenician system democratized writing. Scribes no longer needed a lifetime of training to master thousands of complex characters; anyone could learn to write by mastering a small, flexible set of letters. This phonetic model was subsequently adopted and modified by the Greeks, who introduced vowels, creating the direct precursor to modern Western alphabets.",
