            type: "mc",
            passage: "During the high Middle Ages, European architecture underwent a revolutionary shift with the transition from Romanesque to Gothic styles. Romanesque architecture, which dominated the 11th and early 12th centuries, was characterized by thick walls, heavy masonry, and rounded Roman arches. Because rounded arches push structural weight both downward and outward, they put immense lateral pressure on walls. To prevent collapse, Romanesque architects had to build incredibly thick walls with very few, tiny windows. The resulting interiors were dark, cold, and fortress-like, reflecting a theological focus on solemnity and sanctuary.<br><br>By the mid-12th century, however, master builders in northern France developed a series of structural innovations that birthed the Gothic style, entirely transforming cathedral spaces. The first of these was the pointed arch. Unlike rounded arches, pointed arches channel the weight of the roof downward at a much steeper angle, significantly reducing lateral outward pressure. This allowed vaults to be built much higher and thinner.<br><br>To complement pointed arches, architects developed ribbed vaults—slender intersecting stone arches that supported the ceiling like a skeletal framework. This distributed weight to specific points on the floor rather than continuously along the walls. The crowning innovation was the flying buttress: an exterior arched support that extended from the upper walls down to massive masonry piers far from the cathedral structure. These buttresses absorbed and redirected any remaining lateral thrust safely away from the main building.<br><br>Together, pointed arches, ribbed vaults, and flying buttresses freed the walls from their traditional load-bearing duties. Architects could now replace thick stone with soaring, expansive walls of stained glass, flooding the cathedral interior with light. This structural revolution was driven by a theological shift: light was viewed as a physical manifestation of the divine, and soaring heights were designed to physically draw the eyes and minds of worshippers toward the heavens.",
