            title: "Reading — Artificial Intelligence and the Turing Test",
            desc: "Read the following passage and select the best answer to each question.",
            type: "mc",
            passage: "In 1950, British mathematician and computer pioneer Alan Turing published a seminal paper titled 'Computing Machinery and Intelligence.' At a time when digital computers were in their infancy, Turing was already pondering whether machines could think. Recognizing that defining 'thinking' or 'intelligence' was a philosophical minefield, Turing proposed replacing these ambiguous terms with a practical, behavioral experiment he called the 'Imitation Game,' now universally known as the Turing Test.<br><br>The setup of the test is simple: a human evaluator engages in a text-based conversation with two hidden participants—one human and one computer. If the evaluator cannot reliably distinguish the computer from the human after a set period of conversation, the computer is deemed to have passed the test, demonstrating human-like intelligence. Turing argued that if a machine's linguistic behavior is indistinguishable from a human's, we have no logical basis for denying it the status of a thinking entity.<br><br>Despite its elegance, the Turing Test has faced severe philosophical criticism. The most famous rebuttal is John Searle's 'Chinese Room' thought experiment, proposed in 1980. Searle asks us to imagine a monolingual English speaker locked in a room with a large rulebook of Chinese characters. When Chinese messages are slipped under the door, the speaker uses the rulebook to match incoming symbols with appropriate outgoing symbols, producing fluent Chinese responses. To outsiders, the person in the room appears to understand Chinese perfectly. However, the person is simply manipulating symbols without understanding a single word.<br><br>Searle argued that computers are exactly like the person in the Chinese room: they process syntax (formal rules and symbols) but possess no semantics (true understanding of meaning). Passing the Turing Test, therefore, is merely a demonstration of computational symbol manipulation, not genuine intelligence or consciousness. This debate remains highly relevant today as modern large language models display astonishing conversational abilities while remaining, at their core, sophisticated statistical pattern matchers.",
