            type: "mc",
            passage: "In 1928, Scottish bacteriologist Alexander Fleming returned to his laboratory at St. Mary's Hospital in London after a summer holiday. Before leaving, he had left several Petri dishes of staphylococcus bacteria on his workbench. Upon inspecting the dishes, Fleming noticed something unusual: one plate had been contaminated with a common blue-green mold, <i>Penicillium notatum</i>. More importantly, the staphylococcus bacteria immediately surrounding the mold had been completely destroyed, while bacteria further away remained healthy.<br><br>Fleming deduced that the mold was secreting a substance that actively killed the bacteria. He named this active substance 'penicillin.' Although Fleming published his findings in 1929, the scientific community showed little interest. The main hurdle was that penicillin was highly unstable and difficult to isolate. Fleming lacked the biochemical expertise and resources to purify the active compound in quantities large enough for medical treatment, and he eventually abandoned the project.<br><br>The true medical revolution of penicillin began a decade later at Oxford University. In 1938, pathologist Howard Florey and biochemist Ernst Chain stumbled upon Fleming's paper. Intrigued, they assembled a team to solve the chemical instability of penicillin. By designing innovative cultivation and extraction techniques, Chain successfully isolated stable, purified penicillin, which they proved was highly effective in protecting mice from lethal bacterial infections.<br><br>World War II served as the critical catalyst for penicillin's mass production. With thousands of soldiers dying from wound infections, the British and United States governments partnered with chemical companies to scale up manufacturing. By 1944, penicillin was being produced in massive quantities, saving countless lives on the battlefield and permanently shifting the treatment of infectious diseases from a death sentence to a manageable condition. However, this success also marked the beginning of a modern medical crisis: the rapid emergence of antibiotic-resistant bacterial strains due to widespread over-prescription and mutation.",
