            passage: "Every autumn, millions of Monarch butterflies in North America embark on an extraordinary journey. Traveling up to 4,800 kilometers from southern Canada and the northern United States, they migrate to the high-altitude oyamel fir forests of central Mexico. This migration is uniquely complex because it is multi-generational. Unlike migratory birds, which make the trip multiple times throughout their lives, no individual Monarch ever makes the entire round trip. In fact, the butterflies heading south in autumn are the great-great-grandchildren of those that flew north in the spring.<br><br>This raises a profound biological mystery: how do creatures with brains the size of a pinhead navigate to a specific mountain forest they have never seen? Scientists have discovered that Monarchs rely on a sophisticated 'time-compensated sun compass' in their brains. This navigation system utilizes a sun compass, which reads the angle of the sun on the horizon. However, because the sun moves across the sky as the day progresses, a compass alone would cause the butterflies to fly in circles. To correct for this, the Monarch's brain integrates the sun compass with an internal circadian clock located in their antennae, allowing them to adjust their flight angle continuously and maintain a steady southward trajectory.<br><br>Navigating on cloudy days is made possible by another sensory system: Monarchs can detect polarized light. Although invisible to humans, polarized light creates distinct patterns in the sky that indicate the sun's position even through thick cloud cover.<br><br>The butterflies that make this epic journey belong to a specialized 'migratory generation,' often called the 'super-generation.' While typical summer Monarchs live for only two to six weeks, the super-generation enters a state of reproductive diapause—suspending aging and reproduction. This allows them to live for up to eight months, giving them the physical longevity required to fly all the way to Mexico, survive the winter, and begin the return journey north in the spring.",
