            desc: "Read the following passage and select the best answer to each question.",
            type: "mc",
            passage: "For nearly fifteen centuries, the written language of ancient Egypt was a profound mystery. Following the rise of Christianity in Egypt, the use of hieroglyphs was banned by the Roman Empire in the late 4th century CE to suppress pagan religions. Consequently, the knowledge of how to read and write hieroglyphs was completely lost, and the elegant symbols carved on temple walls were widely dismissed by later historians as mere mystical drawings with no phonetic meaning.<br><br>The key to unlocking this lost world was discovered in 1799 during Napoleon Bonaparte's military campaign in Egypt. French soldiers digging foundations near the port city of Rosetta unearthed a massive slab of black granodiorite, now known as the Rosetta Stone. The stone featured a royal decree issued in 196 BCE on behalf of King Ptolemy V. Crucially, the decree was carved in three different writing systems: hieroglyphs (used for priestly decrees), Demotic (the everyday script of Egyptian administration), and Ancient Greek (the language of the ruling court).<br><br>Because Ancient Greek was well understood by scholars, the Rosetta Stone provided a parallel translation. However, deciphering the hieroglyphs still took more than two decades of intense study. Many scholars clung to the traditional assumption that hieroglyphs were purely ideographic, meaning each symbol represented a complete concept or object rather than a sound.<br><br>The breakthrough came in the 1820s through the work of French linguist Jean-François Champollion. Champollion focused on cartouches—oval frames containing hieroglyphic characters. He hypothesized that these cartouches enclosed the proper names of royalty, such as Ptolemy and Cleopatra. By comparing the phonetic sounds of these names in Greek with the hieroglyphs in the cartouches, Champollion proved that hieroglyphs were not purely symbolic. Instead, they were a highly complex hybrid system: partly logographic, representing ideas, and partly phonetic, representing individual consonant and syllable sounds.",
