            desc: "Read the following passage and select the best answer to each question.",
            type: "mc",
            passage: "The spectacular displays of glowing light that paint the night skies of high-latitude regions—known as the Aurora Borealis in the north and the Aurora Australis in the south—are among the most beautiful natural phenomena on Earth. Despite their mystical appearance, auroras are the result of complex electromagnetic interactions between the Earth's atmosphere, its magnetic field, and the sun.<br><br>The process begins on the sun's surface, which constantly emits a stream of highly energetic, charged particles (primarily electrons and protons) called solar wind. During periods of high solar activity, such as solar flares or coronal mass ejections, the sun releases massive clouds of these particles. Traveling at speeds of up to three million kilometers per hour, the solar wind reaches the Earth in about two to three days.<br><br>As the solar wind approaches Earth, it is blocked by the planet's magnetosphere—a protective magnetic shield generated by the Earth's molten iron core. However, the magnetosphere is not uniform; it is weaker at the polar regions. When the charged solar particles collide with the magnetic field lines, they are funneled down toward the North and South magnetic poles.<br><br>Once these charged particles enter the upper atmosphere (specifically the thermosphere), they collide with atmospheric gas molecules, primarily oxygen and nitrogen. These high-energy collisions transfer energy to the electrons of the gas atoms, pushing them into an 'excited' state. When these excited electrons return to their stable, lower-energy ground states, they release the excess energy as photons of visible light.<br><br>The distinct colors of the aurora depend on the specific altitude and the gas involved. Collisions with oxygen atoms at altitudes of about 100 kilometers produce the most common, brilliant pale-green aurora. At higher altitudes, around 250 kilometers, collisions with oxygen produce a rare red aurora. Meanwhile, nitrogen molecules produce deep blue and violet-purple colors at lower altitudes, creating a dynamic, multicolored curtain of light.",
