            desc: "Read the following passage and select the best answer to each question.",
            type: "mc",
            passage: "For centuries, the vast network of trade routes connecting East Asia to the Mediterranean was known as the 'Silk Road.' Coined by the German geographer Ferdinand von Richthofen in 1877, the term is somewhat misleading. It was never a single, continuous highway, but rather a complex, shifting web of land and sea routes that spanned thousands of kilometers over brutal deserts, treacherous mountain passes, and vast steppes.<br><br>The origin of this trade network dates back to the Chinese Han Dynasty around 130 BCE. Seeking powerful central Asian horses to defend their borders against nomadic invaders, Han emperors sent envoys westward. These missions successfully secured alliances and trade agreements, establishing a safe corridor for merchants. Although China closely guarded the secret of silk production, making it a highly lucrative and prestigious commodity, silk was only one of many goods traded. Jade, spices, tea, and porcelain flowed westward, while Roman glass, gold, wool, and olive oil traveled eastward.<br><br>However, the most lasting historical impact of the Silk Road was not the exchange of physical commodities, but the transmission of culture, technology, and ideas. Religions spread rapidly along these routes; Buddhism traveled from India to China, Korea, and Japan, while Islam spread from the Arabian Peninsula across Central Asia. Technological innovations developed in China, such as paper-making, the magnetic compass, and gunpowder, were carried westward by travelers and merchants, fundamentally altering European and Islamic history.<br><br>Furthermore, the Silk Road facilitated the tragic spread of infectious diseases. The lack of biological immunity along trade routes allowed diseases to travel rapidly. Scholars believe that the Black Death (bubonic plague) was transported along these routes in the 14th century, decimating populations across Asia, the Middle East, and Europe, showing that the connectivity of trade carried profound, often devastating global consequences.",
