            id: "V-10",
            title: "Reading — Deep-Sea Hydrothermal Vents and Extremophiles",
            desc: "Read the following passage and select the best answer to each question.",
            type: "mc",
            passage: "Until 1977, marine biologists believed that all life on Earth was fundamentally dependent on sunlight. Through photosynthesis, plants and algae convert solar energy into organic matter, forming the foundation of almost every food chain. This assumption was shattered when scientists aboard the research submersible <i>Alvin</i> discovered hydrothermal vents along the Galapagos Rift, thousands of meters below the ocean surface.<br><br>At these depths, water pressure is extreme, temperatures are near freezing, and sunlight is entirely absent. Yet, surrounding these volcanic vents—which spew mineral-rich, superheated water reaching temperatures up to 400 degrees Celsius—scientists discovered thriving, complex ecosystems packed with giant tube worms, blind shrimp, and unique crabs. This was a biological impossibility under the photosynthetic paradigm.<br><br>The secret to these deep-sea ecosystems is chemosynthesis, a process carried out by specialized, sulfur-oxidizing bacteria. Hydrothermal vents release vast quantities of hydrogen sulfide—a gas highly toxic to land-based life. Chemosynthetic bacteria absorb this toxic gas and, using oxygen and carbon dioxide, convert chemical energy into organic molecules. This process requires no sunlight whatsoever, serving as the biological engine of the vent ecosystem.<br><br>Many vent animals, such as the giant tube worm (<i>Riftia pachyptila</i>), have evolved remarkable adaptations to survive. These worms have no mouth, eyes, or digestive tract. Instead, they house billions of chemosynthetic bacteria inside a specialized organ called a trophosome. The worm's bright red gills absorb oxygen and hydrogen sulfide from the vent water, transporting these gases through its bloodstream to the bacteria, which in turn feed the worm from within.<br><br>These organisms are classified as 'extremophiles'—microbes and animals that thrive in physical conditions that would instantly kill ordinary life. For astrobiologists, deep-sea hydrothermal vents are of immense scientific value. They prove that life can flourish in the complete absence of sunlight, suggesting that similar chemosynthetic life might exist on icy moons in our solar system, such as Jupiter's Europa or Saturn's Enceladus, which are believed to harbor warm, subsurface oceans beneath their frozen crusts.",
